default2.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAccording to DEFRA, the level of food waste collected and recycled by local councils from households was expected to be 300,000 tonnes
default in 2013. 
default2.6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis volume of food waste can easily be contaminated by plastic bags – in Italy where overall organic recycling is at a similar level to England this result in an extra 64,000 tonnes of waste going to landfill
default.
default2.7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default This results in significant extra costs for councils, and 
defaultt
defaulthere is a significant opportunity to reduce this volume of food going to landfill and the quality of food waste which is then recycled. Compostable bags (already used in food bin caddy liners) have been shown to support both goals – in the UK and Italy. A trial run with the Co-op Supermarket chain in Oldham has shown that organic contamination by traditional plastics dropped by 95% in the area where local retailers promoted compostable carrier bags.
default 
default2.8.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt has also saved the council £2000 in the first three weeks of the trial.
default2.9.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultUnfortunately, 
defaultoxo
default-degradable bags are unsuitable for this purpose as they also contaminate organic recycling. 
