default5.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDuring his evidence Mr Stephen stated there were three international standards for 
defaultoxo
default-degradable plastics. This was not entirely accurate. 
default5.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultStandard BS8472:2011 - “Methods for the assessment of the 
defaultoxo
default-biodegradation of plastics and of the 
defaultphyto
default-toxicity of the residues in controlled laboratory conditions” which as inferred by the title is a laboratory test method, does not contain pass / fail requirements (since it is a test not a specification) and is not applicable in the wider environment.
default&#xa0;
default5.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is no ISO standard specification for 
defaultoxo
default-degradable plastics, there is an ISO test method for ageing of film and an ISO method for determining ultimate biodegradation in soil. No ISO standard specification contains requirements linking the two methods of test.
default&#xa0;
default5.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn response to a comment by Professor Thompson that the research cited regarding biodegradation in the environment required the plastic material to essentially be cooked at high temperature prior to being subjected to biodegradation testing. Mr Stephen said this was a requirement of a laboratory test. With regard to the applicability of the “cooking” in response to the industry response to the Defra EV0422 report in 2012, the research team from Loughborough used the data in the cited study to estimate the oxidation time of the 
defaultoxo
default-degradable plastic in the UK environment with an average temperature of 10 degrees Celsius.
default&#xa0;
default5.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThey concluded that the time for oxidation in the UK environment would be 9 years
default. Mr Stephen told the committee that biodegradation of 
defaultoxo
default-biodegradables takes two years; therefore the conclusion from this research is that this product would take 11 years to biodegrade in the UK environment.
default&#xa0;
default6.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn Italy, a ban and higher charge for bags has seen a dramatic drop in use of throw away plastic bags and littering of them.
default6.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe replacement of traditional bags with compostable 
defaultbioplastic
default bags has seen an improvement in management of food waste – successes which have been repeated in trials in the UK.
default6.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Italian experience has led to the creation of jobs through big, industrial investments in traditional marginal areas
default. A similar regime in the UK could have similar impacts.
